Summary: The occurrence rate of planets as a function of planetary mass and orbital period, and of stellar mass, provides powerful constraints upon models of planet formation, migration, and evolution. Kepler has provided such measurements for FGKM stars, but the short-period planetary population of more massive stars is largely unexplored. It will also provide an excellent sample of planets for studying the impact of high-energy radiation upon planetary atmospheric escape.
